04402nam a22005655i 9780520963214DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20152015cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209632147 a10.1525/97805209632142doi  a(DE-B1597)520148  a(OCoLC)1040263869  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aREL0370002bisacsh04a297.3/709622231 aBrinton, Jacquelene G., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPreaching Islamic Renewal :bReligious Authority and Media in Contemporary Egypt /cJacquelene G. Brinton. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2015] 4cÂ©2015  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Transliterations and Translations -- tIntroduction -- t1. Muhammad Mitwalli Sha'rawi -- t2. Muhammad Mitwalli Sha'rawi and Egyptian Society -- t3. Preaching as a Nexus of 'Ulama' Influence -- t4. Renewal as a Nexus of 'Ulama' Discursive Authority -- t5. Sha'rawi's Knowledge Hierarchy -- t6. Sha'rawi and Sufism in Egypt -- t7. Relevance through Language Use -- t8. Television and the Extension of Authority -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPreaching Islamic Renewal examines the life and work of Muhammad Mitwalli Sha'rawi, one of Egypt's most beloved and successful Islamic preachers. His wildly popular TV program aired every Friday for years until his death in 1998. At the height of his career, it was estimated that up to 30 million people tuned in to his show each week. Yet despite his pervasive and continued influence in Egypt and the wider Muslim world, Sha'rawi was for a long time neglected by academics. While much of the academic literature that focuses on Islam in modern Egypt repeats the claim that traditionally trained Muslim scholars suffered the loss of religious authority, Sha'rawi is instead an example of a well-trained Sunni scholar who became a national media sensation. As an advisor to the rulers of Egypt as well as the first Arab television preacher, he was one of the most important and controversial religious figures in late-twentieth-century Egypt. Thanks to the repurposing of his videos on television and on the Internet, Sha'rawi's performances are still regularly viewed. Jacquelene Brinton uses Sha'rawi and his work as a lens to explore how traditional Muslim authorities have used various media to put forth a unique vision of how Islam can be renewed and revived in the contemporary world. Through his weekly television appearances he popularized long held theological and ethical beliefs and became a scholar-celebrity who impacted social and political life in Egypt.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aIslamic preachingxEgypt. 0aIslamic preachingzEgypt. 0aTelevision in religionxEgyptxEgypt. 0aTelevision in religionzEgypt. 7aRELIGION / Islam / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311062111208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016z978311065748740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520963214423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520963214.jpg  a978-3-11-062111-2  UC Press eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-065748-7  UCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles